Sure! Here's an example of how you could include React.js to the app:

1. Install React.js and related dependencies via npm:
```
npm install react react-dom
```
1. Create a React component, for example, a simple counter component:
```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const increment = () => setCount(count + 1);
  const decrement = () => setCount(count - 1);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Counter</h2>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={increment}>+</button>
      <button onClick={decrement}>-</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default Counter;
```
1. Add the React component to the app:
```jsx
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';
import Counter from './Counter';

ReactDOM.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <Counter />
  </React.StrictMode>,
  document.getElementById('root')
);
```
1. Add a `div` element with an `id` of `root` to the HTML file:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>My App</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="root"></div>
    <script src="./index.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```
1. Finally, run the app with a tool like `webpack` or `parcel`.

Certainly, here is an example of a React component that can be used for the UI front end:
```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

const App = () => {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchData = async () => {
      const result = await axios(
        'http://example.com/api/data',
      );
      setData(result.data);
    };
    fetchData();
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Farm Management Dashboard</h1>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Field Name</th>
            <th>Crop</th>
            <th>Soil Moisture</th>
            <th>Temperature</th>
            <th>Humidity</th>
            <th>Status</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {data.map(item => (
            <tr key={item.id}>
              <td>{item.field_name}</td>
              <td>{item.crop}</td>
              <td>{item.soil_moisture}</td>
              <td>{item.temperature}</td>
              <td>{item.humidity}</td>
              <td>{item.status}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```
This component fetches data from an API endpoint and displays it in a table. You can modify the component to include other features and functionality based on the requirements of your farm management app.
